Here's what the canonical example taught us and how the structure changed:

Official pattern (from geo_choropleth): GeoJSON as primary data → CSV as lookup. This keeps the geometry on the primary row so geoshape can render it directly without the "shape" encoding channel hack. For static data that works perfectly.

Why we still need CSV-primary here: the official example has no year dimension — it's one lookup with a fixed CSV. For your case, the filter: "datum.year == year_select" needs to run on the data that has the year column, which is the CSV. You can't filter a lookup source in Vega-Lite. So CSV stays primary and GeoJSON is the lookup — same as before — but now the spec is structured more idiomatically:

data and transform sit at the top level, shared across all layers (the official example's style)
Layer 1 inherits everything and just declares mark + encoding
Layer 2 overrides data with the hardcoded label centroids — layers can always override parent data
