Diagnosed rendering issue and restructured data architecture approach
Diagnosed rendering issue and restructured data architecture approach
The colours are working but shapes still invisible — the shape encoding with a CSV-primary lookup isn't rendering geometry correctly. The canonical Vega-Lite pattern must be GeoJSON as primary, CSV as lookup (not the reverse). Let me fix the direction:


Ran a command, read a file
Ran a command, read a file
The core mistake across all three versions was the lookup direction. Here's the exact reason shapes weren't rendering:

When CSV is primary and you lookup "fields": ["geometry"] from GeoJSON, Vega fetches the raw geometry JSON object and puts it in datum.geometry. Then "shape": {"field": "geometry", "type": "geojson"} tries to render it — but this encoding channel only works when Vega has already parsed the geometry through the geojson format pipeline. A plain JSON object in a field doesn't work the same way.

The canonical pattern (and the only way shapes render) is:

GeoJSON as primary data  →  Vega parses geometry automatically
     ↓
Lookup CSV by properties.state_code  →  fire_risk_score, state_code etc. join onto each feature row
     ↓
geoshape mark renders using the pre-parsed geometry, color encodes fire_risk_score
No "shape" encoding needed at all — when GeoJSON is primary, geoshape knows what to draw. The state_code field is also fetched from the CSV lookup so datum.state_code is available for the state_select highlight conditions and for the JS click handler's item.datum.state_code.


